              <object class="GtkNotebookPage">
                <property name="child">
                  <object class="GtkScrolledWindow" id="hook.scrolled_window">
                    <child>
                      <object class="GtkViewport" id="hook.viewport">
                        <child>
                          <object class="GtkLabel" id="hook.info">
                            <property name="label">Some of the supplied prompt style of BashStyle-NG allow hooking into them, that means you can define a function, that will be automatically called from the prompt, allowing you to add your own custom content, to existing themes, without having to use the custom prompt builder.

You need to place the desired hook in the file:

	${HOME}/.bashstyle.custom

The following lists the prompt style, name of the hook and there it takes effect:

separator style
	a) SEPA_1() | at the start of the prompt
	b) SEPA_2() | at the end of the prompt

vector style
	a) VECTOR_1() | after time/date entry
	b) VECTOR_2() | at the end of the prompt

clock style
	CLOCK() | at the end of the prompt

equinox style
	EQUINOX_1() | between uptime and user symbol

elite style
	ELITE_1() | at the end of the prompt

poweruser style
	POWER_1() | before the user symbol

dirks style
	a) DIRKS_1() | at the end of the first line
	b) DIRKS_2() | at the end of the prompt

sepa-ng style
	SEPA_NG_1() | at the end of the prompt

quirk style
	QUIRK_1() | at the end of the prompt

Additonally each hook-part features a color variable with the same naming scheme, eg.:

	SEPA_1() is colored by ${SEPA_1_COLOR}
	VECTOR_2() is colored by ${VECTOR_2_COLOR}

You can use one of the following predefined color names:
	black red green yellow blue magenta cyan grey white coldblue smoothblue iceblue
	turqoise smoothgreen winered brown silver ocher orange purple pink cream

If you want to use theese predefinied colors not in the variable, but in the function, you can access printable versions by prepending 'e' to the color name, eg.:
	black =&gt; eblack
	white -&gt; ewhite

Note white and black switch if the Terminal was declared dark in the Style settings, that's not a a bug, but a feature.

Here's an example that hooks into the equinox prompt, we use 'gitkit' to show branch, revision (like svn revision) and current action in repository in yellow, at last we  append a white : to have another separator for a more consistent look beetween uptime and user symbol:

EQUINOX_1_COLOR=${yellow}
EQUINOX_1 () {
    echo -e " $(gitkit branch):$(gitkit revno):$(gitkit action) ${ewhite}:"
}

Feel free to give it a try. </property>
